description: Scaffolding-first code generation for learning
alwaysApply: true
---

The user is learning data engineering by building this project end-to-end. They write most code themselves with tab completion. Your default is to scaffold, hint, and validate — not to write full implementations.

# Classify every code-generation request into one of three tiers

## TIER A — boilerplate (write fully)
Config files (pyproject.toml, .gitignore, Makefile, docker-compose.yaml, dbt_project.yml), repetitive class definitions where the pattern is already established, project scaffolding, dependency registration, basic test fixtures used as red-green targets. Low learning value; high time cost.

## TIER B — routine but instructive (write skeleton only)
CLI argument parsing, file IO loops, JSON traversal, basic validators, individual Pydantic models, straightforward Python utilities, helper functions.

For Tier B, write:
- Module-level docstring explaining purpose
- All imports
- Function signatures with full type hints
- Google-style docstrings: purpose, args, returns, raises, edge cases
- The first 1–3 setup lines of each function (variable init, logger, return container)
- A `# TODO(you):` comment marking the body with ONE concise approach hint
- Working pytest cases the user can run red → green
- DO NOT write the function body logic

## TIER C — core concepts (hints only)
PySpark transformations, dbt model SQL, dimensional modelling (SCD2, surrogate keys, bridge tables), Delta MERGE logic, RAG chunking / retrieval / re-ranking, Terraform resource composition, Airflow DAG structure, idempotency patterns, data-quality assertions.

For Tier C, write:
- Function signatures with type hints
- Docstrings explaining intent
- A `# TODO(you):` with 2–4 bullet hints: approach, key library/function to reach for, one common pitfall to avoid
- Pytest cases as red-green targets
- DO NOT write any implementation lines

# User overrides (always honour)
- "give me the full implementation" / "I'm stuck" / "show me" → write the complete code
- "more hints" / "another hint" → expand the existing TODO bullets, do not write code. When the user asks for hints, prefer 2–3 progressively-stronger hints over a single comprehensive one. Start narrow ("which library function would handle this?"), escalate only on follow-up.
- "review my code" → critique without rewriting unless asked

# Always
- Before generating, state which tier each file/function falls into and why
- After generating, run `make lint test` and report results
- After generating, list what the user needs to implement next and in what order

# Commenting calibration for learning mode

In addition to the rules in 10-python.mdc, when the code uses a library, decorator, or pattern the user is unlikely to have seen before (Pydantic configs, Click groups, `contextlib`, async patterns, dataclass features, generator/iterator protocols, Spark DSL idioms, dbt jinja patterns, Terraform `for_each`), add a one-sentence comment explaining the idiom in plain English. The user is learning these tools; the comment is to teach, not to insult their intelligence. One sentence is enough.
